snippet.textDisplay:
In early 2000, 16 year old me was able to do work experience at Nintendo Australia - where they had their hotline office for "The Game Guru's". By the second day I was hanging out there until 9pm, which no one had tried before and probably no one did after, based on the wrist slap I got by Friday afternoon.
The call centre was just 10 guys playing games at desks, talking about gaming news, playing EEPROM's of yet to be released titles (I got to play Perfect Dark 4 months in advance), receiving calls and answering from memory or via their databases. Even then it was odd as the internet was very much a thing. But the hotline did get its business from print media afterall.

What made it less of a cheat and more of a human connection was the way that people had to describe where they are in a game, the guru's had to work that out and then describe to them what they had to do, often in real time or to the player jotting it down with pen and paper. It'd be pretty neat if a streamer were able to recreate a game guide hotline with real people calling in, with the modern ability of sharing a screen shot of where they're stuck etc. Today that could mean everything from a NES game to a new PS4 game and everything in between, cross platform baaaayyybbeeeee.

snippet.textDisplay: When I was younger I got stuck in the Forbidden Woods while playing Wind Waker and couldn't for the life of me figure out how to get past it. My older brother ended up buying me a Prima Guide for it, and honestly I loved it since it not only got me past that part I was stuck on, but it had a bunch of nice little pieces of artwork I had never seen before. It even came with a map of the Great Sea poster!! It's the only guide I own to this day thanks to the internet, but I'm glad I was given it as a gift as opposed to being pointed to a line on a web page and being told "that's what you have to do".

snippet.textDisplay: Back when I was but a young teen during the PS1 days I seen those walkthrough magazines everywhere. I was really into rpg's like FF7, FF8, and lots of others!  I was also majorly into Tomb Raider, so much so that before I had a memory card I would play and see how far I could get. It was essentially like playing HARDCORE MODE where I had to beat it with one life. Death meant starting all over, so when I finally got a memory card it was SO much easier lol. But yeah, my uncle had a friend who would always buy a strategy guide with any new game with big, single-player stories.  I never understood that because I felt like he was robbing himself of the real.experience.  Seems like a guide is the worst spoiler ever!

snippet.textDisplay:
Third-party strategy guides have done overall more harm than good in this world. Final Fantasy XI players (yes, the first one that was an MMO; you can presumably already start to see the problem here) have either repressed memories of or suffer PTSD from the horrors of the dreaded Brady guide that some . . . we'll generously say "less-than-savvy" players seemed to treat as gospel. In a game that routinely required players to coordinate to get anything done, which in turn required them to know what they're doing, the mere existence Bradygames actively detracted from the playability of FFXI.


Furthermore, anybody who's even skimmed through a Prima Pokémon Strategy Guide can safely say "good riddance to bad rubbish;" in a game with hundreds of monsters to keep track of, the "not knowing what you're talking about" error rate becomes an easily calculable percentage.

snippet.textDisplay:
Walkthroughs used to be a work of art. I owned every Final Fantasy (and many other RPGs) strategy guide before I had even played them all. I had memorized every secret in Zelda, Mario 3, etc. I would take them to school and read them all day long. It resulted in me becoming a living walkthrough for how to beat just about any game my circle of friends were playing (this was before widespread access to the internet). It got to the point where I was hardly even playing games anymore, just reading about them. Everyone came to me for information about games.

Scott, you should have totally brought up Final Fantasy IX’s abysmal PlayOnline integration.

Edit: nevermind, you did bring it up, you sly fox.
